loitered upon the doorstep, looking round at the silent square, with its blank, closeshuttered windows and its staring blinds. The sky was pure opal now, and the roofs of
the houses glistened like silver against it. From some chimney opposite a thin wreath
of smoke was rising. It curled, a violet riband, through the nacre-coloured air.
In the huge gilt Venetian lantern, spoil of some Dogeâ€™s barge, that hung from the
ceiling of the great, oak-panelled hall of entrance, lights were still burning from three
flickering jets: thin blue petals of flame they seemed, rimmed with white fire. He turned
them out and, having thrown his hat and cape on the table, passed through the library 
towards the door of his bedroom, a large octagonal chamber on the ground floor that,
in his new-born feeling for luxury, he had just had decorated for himself and hung with
some curious Renaissance tapestries that had been discovered stored in a disused attic
at Selby Royal. As he was turning the handle of the door, his eye fell upon the portrait
Basil Hallward had painted of him. He started back as if in surprise. Then he went on
into his own room, looking somewhat puzzled. After he had taken the button-hole out
of his coat, he seemed to hesitate. Finally, he came back, went over to the picture, and
examined it. In the dim arrested light that struggled through the cream-coloured silk
